headline: President Trump rips Democrats' new probe as a 'hoax'
subHeadline: Trump fights back after House Democrats launch an expansive new investigation; reaction and analysis on 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino along with Jedediah Bila, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is “The Five.” President Trump fighting back after House Democrats launched an expansive new investigation. House Judiciary Chairman Jerrold Nadler requesting documents from 81 people and organizations associated with the president. Nadler defending the move.

utterances.speaker: REP. JERROLD NADLER, D-N.Y.
utterances.sentences: We're simply exercising our oversight jurisdiction. You've had two years of sustained attacks by the administration of nature that we haven't seen probably in a century or more against the free press, against the courts, against the law enforcement administrations, against freedom of speech. We have to make sure this is not a dictatorship and that the rule of law is respected.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: President Trump blasting the new probe.

utterances.speaker: DONALD TRUMP, PRESIDENT
utterances.sentences: The witch hunt continues. I guess that -- I guess we've got 81 letters. There was no collusion. That was a hoax. There was no anything. And they want to do that instead of getting legislation passed, and it's a disgrace. It's a disgrace to our country. I'm not surprised it's happening. Basically they've started a campaign, so the campaign begins. But they just haven't gotten used to the fact that we won a lot of states that haven't been won by Republicans in a long time. Instead of doing infrastructure, instead of doing health care, instead of doing so many things that they should be doing, they want to play games.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Infrastructure week is going to be awesome, Jesse --

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, HOST
utterances.sentences: It sure is.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- when they get around to it. So calls for impeachment are hard to control when the base wants what it wants. And it's just --they're going to keep asking for it. And these -- even if they want to tap the brakes, they're being pushed into it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, it's a runaway train and the media is fueling the fire as well. These numbers from the president that just came out are pretty spectacular, and the NBC poll approval ratings at 46 percent. Rasmussen is at 48. Harvard and Harris have him at 45. Blacks, he's in the mid-20's? Mid-20's. And then the base, the Republicans have him at 93. Sorry, haters. So despite all of the stuff they've thrown at this guy, you know, the spies, the lies, the probes, the 25th amendment, all of this stuff, his numbers are at or near record highs. So the buzz from the Mueller report is there's not going to be all this collusion that they're going to report. So the Democrats are getting nervous and they're scrambling for new crimes. And it doesn't look like they've found any in the House report, in the Senate report, in the counter intel probe. And the sentencing memos from Mueller indicate that they don't really have anything there.  So the bottom line is this, there is nothing that the middle-class can look and see what the Democrats are doing and say this affects my life. This is what I want. I want to see Trump's taxes. I want these investigations. I want Don Jr. up on the hill. It doesn't deliver and the polling never shows it delivers. If I were the president, I would cooperate but I would -- I would call privilege on a lot of this stuff, the same way Barack Obama did.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah. And also just speaking of that, Jedediah, Politico reporting that the Democrats do plan to demand President Trump's tax returns in about two weeks, which I guess -- it's closer to tax day.

utterances.speaker: JEDEDIAH BILA, HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Maybe that's what they're looking for.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I mean, only 81 entities. They're getting lazy. I mean, I was hoping for at least 100 or 150. It's basically -- it's ridiculous. This is so desperate now that even people who were originally on board saying, look, if there was collusion with Russia, let's investigate it.  Let's figure out. All the rational people have left the room. And now, everyone that's left is looking at this and saying, OK, these are people who are dissatisfied with the election results. They don't have an agenda of their own that's appealing to people. What are you going to go out to most of the country and talk the way AOC does? Socialism. A green new deal. None of this stuff makes practical sense to the average person.  The average person in the United States is not a socialist. They see that, it sounds extreme. Democrats need to learn, though, you're not going to win an election by going after the other guy and being constantly negative about him. You have to bring something positive to the table yourself. So they either need to be proud of this very, very extreme agenda that includes late-term abortion. Let them talk about infanticide and getting rid of all the electric cars in ten years. Either, be proud of that, put that front and center, and make that -- do what you've got to do and create some optimism there. Or leave the room because you are giving Trump a victory right now by doing this and the poll numbers show that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Juan, can the Democrats do that? Will it continue to go after President Trump, but also, maybe, meet him on infrastructure bill or something like that? Like, is there a way for them to actually do both with a base that really wants them to just fight?

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, HOST
utterances.sentences: No, I think the base wants them to legislate as well as investigate. I don't think there's any problem there. I think they can do two things at one time. I must say I have a very different view. And I look at the poll numbers, 45, 46 percent, that's his high, Jesse. It's not high for most presidents.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I understand. But that's still his high.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: But his high is good, right? I mean --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: That's not good.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's the same way Obama's was --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, that's true. But remember, Obama was at a low point. This guy is at his high point. But here's the thing, if you look at those numbers, 64 percent of Americans right now think that the president should release his tax returns. That's two-thirds of the American people. How about this? Half of the respondents, this Quinnipiac poll that came out today, think that they believe -- guess -- this is so unbelievable to me, they believe Cohen more than they believed Trump, 64 percent think that Trump committed crimes before he was President of the United States.  So Republicans have a strong affinity for the constitution as it was written. And the constitution is very clear. Congress is an equal branch of government with oversight responsibilities, and they need to gather facts in the course of exercising oversight before they come to any kind of decision about impeachment and the like. But Republicans are acting like, oh, it's impeachment right now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Let me get Greg in please.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm sorry, what?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: We have talked about how Democrats -- maybe it would be helpful for President Trump to have someone to fight against, right? So now he has somebody to push back against. And now the Democrats are kind of providing him that which I think makes him look more like a statesmen.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.sentences: Imagine that you're like a surgeon or an air traffic controller, right, doing your job and outside the window is like a birthday clown juggling chainsaws. That's the Democrats. Their role right now, simply, is to distract a man from doing his job. The problem is he's America's air-traffic controller. He's America's surgeon. So a lot of people kind of don't like this distraction. Let's say you have a normal job. I was thinking about this today. Let's say you have a normal job. You're an electrician or an insurance agent, and all the sudden your boss comes in and says, hey, you know what, I'd like you to devote more time into investigating that electrician across the street or devote more time to investigating that insurance agent across the street.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes. As if you have time, right? You have time to do this. So what I'm learning is these politicians have a lot of time to do this sort of thing. In a sense, they're creating an argument for their own uselessness, that they're able to do unending investigations. At best, being a congressman is a part-time job. It's a seasonal occupation, like being a department store Santa or an NFL ref. And what we have done by allowing them to have a full-time job is we're allowing them to investigate instead of legislate.  I've learned everything and it's left or right or center, this should not be a full-time job. And I think that you have to be better than the people who upset you. Eight years ago there were people like this about Obama, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: They were people that were convinced Obama was going to be a dictator, right? He was going to seize power. You're just doing what they're doing. You're just doing -- you are now a mirror of the people you despised. You should step out of this and look down and see that you're no better than they are.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Democrats do -- Jesse, I'll give you the last word. The Democrats do say that Republicans went way overboard investigating Obama, and they could point to all sorts of hearings and document requests and trying to gum up the works, and being the clown outside the airplane.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I thought those were legitimate investigations where Americans died. And Americans died in fast and furious. What's so funny, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, because --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Do you think it's funny that they died in fast and furious?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'm saying --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Do you think it's funny that they've died in the end?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You've said oversight, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse, you said it's totally legitimate when Republicans do it, but illegitimate when Democrats do it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: It's scale, Juan. If there's a dead American, I want my Congress to investigate it, Republican or Democrat. Who's dead? The only thing dead is the Democrats' electoral chances in 2020, and that's what this is all about.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Can I speak?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think that you are arguing that this president should be immune from accountability --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, I'm not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: He's been the most accountable president --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Hold on. Hold on. Are you arguing --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- and more sunlight on this guy than any other president I can even remember, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: OK. So you're arguing then that if there's a conflict of interest, if he has, in fact, some kind of ties with Russia during the course --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Let Mueller decide it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Republicans --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I'm willing to look at the Mueller report, Juan. You know it's not going to deliver the goods. And that's why they're doing all these other investigations.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think you're hopeful. But I'm saying Congress has legitimate responsibility. Why are you so upset when Democrats exercise that responsibility but not upset when Republicans went on for five years about --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't look upset, Juan. I'm actually happy.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Everybody is yelling and we've got to move on. All right, up next, Congressmen Ilhan Omar facing new accusation of anti-Semitism, will Democrats move to condemn her?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Welcome back. Congressman Ilhan Omar being accused of making new anti-Semitic remarks. Omar facing Republican backlash and there's some feuding with members of her own party after she said this.

utterances.speaker: REP. ILHAM OMAR, D-MINN.
utterances.sentences: Talk about the political influence in this country that says it is OK for people to push for allegiance of foreign country.

utterances.speaker: OMAR
utterances.sentences: Why is it OK for me to talk about the influence of the NRA, or fossil fuel industries, or big pharma, and not talk about a powerful lobbying group that is influencing policy?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: In response to those remarks, Democrats could vote tomorrow on a resolution to condemn anti-Semitism. The party, however, is split over whether to include Omar's name in the resolution. So, Dana, let's just go to the heart of the matter because there're people who are saying she's talking about American policy in the Middle East. Why is that anti- Semitic?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, it's because there's a code, right? So she also talks about dual loyalty. That's what she's suggesting is that people who support the State of Israel, that if they're Jewish, that you, actually -- your loyalty is not just to the United States. Your loyalty is Israel. And it's been something that has been considered anti-Semitic and goes way back. And so -- perhaps she didn't know initially that when she said that, that that was offensive. But the thing is, now she's been told so many times that you have to wonder like how do you solve -- from the musical, how do you solve a problem like Maria? I think that's what the Democrats are -- like how do you solve this problem of Congresswoman Omar because this is a story that keeps coming back over and over again. To the extent that Mark Mehlman who's a Democratic pollster, kind of guy, a consultant, they've started a group, Democrats for Israel, right? Like to explain to people why if you're Jewish and you're a Democrat, you should be supportive. And they have to do like a whole reeducation -- that's probably the wrong word. But education to people who are younger, somebody like Congresswoman Omar who is younger, but this is not -- she's not an isolated case. Like this is being taught across universities and, in particular, the BDS movement to try to divest from anything that has to do with Jewish people or Israel. That -- it's growing and so I think that there does need to be a decision by the Democrats, and I think they would be smart to go ahead and take it on now because it's clearly not going to get better.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, Jesse, in fact, a lot of people argue that this is not about Jewish people, that the biggest supporters of Israel are evangelical Christians and the Republican Party on the right that have made Israel into a sort of a litmus test for themselves. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Well, I mean, this is universal condemnation from -- to Omar. I mean, Nancy Pelosi, the anti-defamation league, the Jewish policy center have all said that what she said is offensive and prejudice. It's not something that the evangelical right is creating here as a wedge issue.  She reminds me, you know, of a freshman in college, like two weeks into the semester, first term, she's already on probation. She's already had her parents called. This is not good. I mean, she's barely a freshman and she's already getting spanked by the leadership. It's humiliating to her and it's got to be humility to the Democratic leadership right now. If you combine her with AOC's green new deal and then she stepped in with this, you know, felony campaign finance scandal, and then the other Tlaib woman with the -- impeachment rhetoric that came out of her mouth, these three radical musketeers are causing a big problem for the Democratic Party. And I guarantee you there's some picture of her with Farrakhan or someone that's about to drop. If you look -- we've talked about this the other day. She wrote that letter of support to ISIS recruits. She's traffic in anti-Semitic tropes. She's used, kind of, money language about Jewish people and their influence. And she has been educated. The Jewish community in her district in Minnesota had a big summit with her. They called it an anti-Semitic intervention and they told her this, you can't say this, this is the history of the Jewish people, and she still doesn't get it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I mean, in fact, the West Virginia GOP put up a poster, linked her to 9/11, totally illegitimate. But, again, these are attacks against her. And so, Greg, the question becomes should she be stripped of her seat on the foreign affairs committee?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I don't think she should have ever gotten the seat to begin with. And, you know, I have a hard time with language being over parsed because - - that's what we are doing these days on both sides. And I think the left is harder on the right in this case. I mean, they come after -- they try to believe that what you said mean something else. She can say what she wants. She just has to live with it. What bugs me about her is -- there's this other hypocrisy that she gets away with. The lesbian, gay, bisexual, LGBTQ -- am I missing one?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No, Q is the end.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Q is the end. Who are kind of -- are OK with what's not being said. So the only -- the most friendly country in the Middle East for gays is Israel, right? And that's the country she keeps harping on, and I don't think that's a coincidence because what are the other countries that -- it is definitely linked to her religious background. But that somehow skates by as everybody makes fun of Mike Pence, her religion makes Mike Pence look like Freddie Mercury. So -- I think that's something -- I think that's something that is, kind of like not discussed that probably could be raised, like, what are her thoughts? I know that she comes out in defense of the community here, but what about her affiliations to those other countries?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, Jedediah, I think the heart and soul of what she has to say is about the way Israel deals with the Palestinians. About Benjamin Netanyahu, the Israeli leader, rebuffed the U.S. on an idea of a two-state solution which had been long-term U.S. policy in the Middle East. She wants to talk about this and everybody immediately says, well, you said this and it wasn't explicitly anti-Semitic but it could be viewed that way. And she's -- she feels like she's being silenced. You can't speak out about Israel in this country.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: She's being anti-Semitic, and the problem is she has a long history of making those comments. You go back to 2012 and she was talking about, you know, Israel has hypnotized the world --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: -- she has repeatedly had to -- she's made statements that people have found deeply offensive and anti-Semitic, repeatedly had to apologize. The behavior persists. She knows that this stuff is not going to be received well. She made that comment about it's all about the Benjamins. She -- look, if she wants to make a comment about Israel, she needs to watch the way she's wording these things. She is deeply, deeply offending a vast majority of Jewish people in this country. And I think --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I don't think it's Jewish people. I think it's those Christian evangelicals --

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: No, no, please, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She's getting condemned by the party leadership.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Yes. And she cannot say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Not Republican Party leadership.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, because she's opening the door to these attacks.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Her name needs to be mentioned in that resolution because she is not stopping and that needs to be a deeply embarrassing moment. Democrats need to unify and say enough is enough because this doesn't -- she's doing them no favors either. Other Democrats do not want to be linked to this. Maybe AOC or other extremists can get out there in defense some of this language, but this is just not acceptable. And most Democrats know this isn't acceptable, they're not OK with it. And they're having a really hard time that someone from their party is getting away with repeatedly this type of horrific anti-Semitism.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right, Joe Biden getting some bad news about 2020. Find out about that bad news next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Oh, Joe Biden is leading in 2020 polls, but he may want to think twice before jumping into the race. A focus group of Democratic voters telling the former V.P., sorry, Joe, we're just not that into you. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: How many of you would like to see Joe Biden get in? Show of hands. What's happening?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: His time is done.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I'll be honest. I used to think, like, you know, because -- I was -- he was riding like the Obama wave, and I thought he was the person that would unite the party, but to be honest, you know, Senator Biden really comes from kind of the good old boy politics of the past.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Tough crowd. That same focus group also urged Hillary to stay far away from 2020, and it seems like they may get their wish, kind of.

utterances.speaker: HILLARY CLINTON, D-FORMER PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.sentences: I'm not running, but I'm going to keep working and speaking and standing up for what I believe. I want to be sure that people understand I'm going to keep speaking out. I'm not going anywhere.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: What do you think, Juan, first about Biden, that cold reception? I seem to be hearing a lot of that that they want new blood. That they want the more progressive wing of the Democratic Party to step forward, that he's too moderate, he's too bland. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I think, Jedediah, what Democrats wants is somebody who can beat Donald Trump. I think likability is number one. And so, when you start asking people about Joe Biden's politics, people will say, well, I didn't like the way he treated Anita Hill, or I don't like the way he dealt with the criminal reform bill in the '90s, or I didn't like the way that he handled some issues with President Obama, and they start bringing up all sorts of things that he said in the past. But I think when you look at the actual polls, not just the focus group of a limited number, the most recent polls had Biden with 37 percent of Democrats saying he's their number one choice, and 51 percent saying he's one of their top choices. Wow. So, I mean, right now he has the luxury of time because he's the front runner. He's got the money. He's got the staff.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: He's got the name recognition.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yes. So, I mean, Bloomberg, Mike Bloomberg the former mayor of New York, today said he's not running. Hillary Rodham Clinton says she's not running. I think a lot of them are looking to Joe Biden. There some other people on the edge, a Sherrod Brown, Terry McAuliffe who would occupy that kind of centrist lane for Democrats. And the centrist lane is very important because it has the advantage of saying I can appeal to people in such a way as to ensure we beat Trump.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Now I know you're very upset, Jesse, that Hillary is not going to be running. The only person on Earth that's more upset than you is Donald Trump. He actually tweeted about this today. You guys have that so we can read for people -- oh, there we go. Crooked Hillary Clinton confirms she will not run in 2020, rules out a third bid for the White House. Ah, shucks, does that mean I won't get to run against her again? She will be sorely missed. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Third time is a charm, Hillary. I would say please reconsider, would love to have you back in the race.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Well, the good news is she's going to be out there stumping for people if they want her, so --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I know a lot of people don't want her. I heard a lot -- remember the last election, a lot of people didn't want her husband, Bill. They wanted to keep him at arm's length, but I bet you'd see a lot of people keeping her at arm's length, especially in some of the swing state, in the rust belt that she lost marvelously. As far as Biden goes, I agree, you know, people want the new car smell. And the zeitgeist of the Democratic Party is they want the opposite of Donald Trump. They want a young female socialist with a blank slate who can just go there and punch the president in the mouth and take him down. But everybody knows deep down, and no one knows this, deep down he knows and everybody else does, they do not have a candidate that they feel confident at this point that can beat Donald Trump and it is very hard to take out an incumbent.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Dana, what do you think Obama makes of this though. A rejection of Biden. You know people don't want Hillary Clinton around maybe potentially. I think just happens to be right on that. Is that kind of a rejection of his legacy? Does he want Biden to be the guy front and center?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think he doesn't want to have to be put in the middle and to choose and he probably understands the idea that you would want new blood and a new car smell, because he was that in 2008. And that's how he was able to beat Hillary Clinton. For Joe Biden, he has the life of a private citizen, but it comes with the scrutiny of a public official. And that's because if you look at for example the Democrats already given him a hard time, because he's out there giving $200,000 speeches or do, we have the transcripts of those speeches. Also, he's doing all these public events actively talking about whether he's going to run. He's thinking about it. They can't decide, can't decide. So, he had plenty of time to make a decision. But I think because he's put himself out there so much to keep the name recognition up that people are like, yes, we already saw that show. We don't want that show again.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: I get the desire for new blood, new ideas, freshness, I get that, but that happens to be on the Democratic side, a very extreme wing. I wonder why they're not afraid of that to put the socialist front and center, that doesn't register for them?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Well, the party needs new blood, but so does Joe. I can't believe we're taking this seriously. A six person focus group on CNN. I mean this was a slow news day. I give you - it was a slow news day. If we were trolling for crap off of CNN, a six person focus group. I'm sorry, it wasn't crap. It was just six people. All right. I don't trust CNN after what they did to Sanders--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: By the way, isn't it astounding that you and I agree.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's true. Gosh, what a night to agree. No, it's true. It's like number one, we know that C and CNN stands for Kamala. I changed the spelling. But they do take - I think they've already supported. They've already backing her. They don't want Sanders, remember how they got rid of Sanders. They don't want Joe--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Are you saying that CNN stacked the focus group.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I am saying exactly that, Jesse. I'm saying exactly - in fact, I think they all work for Kamala Harris, right. No, no, he flunks the intersectionality quiz. He's an old white male in Democratic Party terms. He's got rickets.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I don't even know what rickets are.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: But for the record, I think that focus group is dead on. I think it's representative of a lot of people.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Six person focus group.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That simple.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.sentences: Company makes a surprising discovery about the gender wage gap. Details coming up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I know. For years, the media has told us that men get paid way more than women for the same work. But when you look closely at the details, the differences tend to shrink even disappear. Take Google who has been accused of underpaying female workers. But when they investigated this charge, they found what, they indeed were underpaying men. There goes another narrative. Now this should be good news. It's progress for women, right. Instead however advocates and their supportive media simply say that equal pay must mask a more hidden discrimination. Now why would they say that? Two reasons, one for many advocates progress can be bad because an end to inequality means the advocates are out of work, so their role is less about helping people than ensuring a livelihood. utterances.utterance: No, I think the base wants them to legislate as well as investigate. I don't think there's any problem there. I think they can do two things at one time. I must say I have a very different view. And I look at the poll numbers, 45, 46 percent, that's his high, Jesse. It's not high for most presidents.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I understand. But that's still his high.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: But his high is good, right? I mean --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: That's not good.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's the same way Obama's was --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, that's true. But remember, Obama was at a low point. This guy is at his high point. But here's the thing, if you look at those numbers, 64 percent of Americans right now think that the president should release his tax returns. That's two-thirds of the American people. How about this? Half of the respondents, this Quinnipiac poll that came out today, think that they believe -- guess -- this is so unbelievable to me, they believe Cohen more than they believed Trump, 64 percent think that Trump committed crimes before he was President of the United States. So Republicans have a strong affinity for the constitution as it was written. And the constitution is very clear. Congress is an equal branch of government with oversight responsibilities, and they need to gather facts in the course of exercising oversight before they come to any kind of decision about impeachment and the like. But Republicans are acting like, oh, it's impeachment right now.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Let me get Greg in please.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm sorry, what?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We have talked about how Democrats -- maybe it would be helpful for President Trump to have someone to fight against, right? So now he has somebody to push back against. And now the Democrats are kind of providing him that which I think makes him look more like a statesmen.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, HOST
utterances.utterance: Imagine that you're like a surgeon or an air traffic controller, right, doing your job and outside the window is like a birthday clown juggling chainsaws. That's the Democrats. Their role right now, simply, is to distract a man from doing his job. The problem is he's America's air-traffic controller. He's America's surgeon. So a lot of people kind of don't like this distraction. Let's say you have a normal job. I was thinking about this today. Let's say you have a normal job. You're an electrician or an insurance agent, and all the sudden your boss comes in and says, hey, you know what, I'd like you to devote more time into investigating that electrician across the street or devote more time to investigating that insurance agent across the street.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes. As if you have time, right? You have time to do this. So what I'm learning is these politicians have a lot of time to do this sort of thing. In a sense, they're creating an argument for their own uselessness, that they're able to do unending investigations. At best, being a congressman is a part-time job. It's a seasonal occupation, like being a department store Santa or an NFL ref. And what we have done by allowing them to have a full-time job is we're allowing them to investigate instead of legislate. I've learned everything and it's left or right or center, this should not be a full-time job. And I think that you have to be better than the people who upset you. Eight years ago there were people like this about Obama, right?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: They were people that were convinced Obama was going to be a dictator, right? He was going to seize power. You're just doing what they're doing. You're just doing -- you are now a mirror of the people you despised. You should step out of this and look down and see that you're no better than they are.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Democrats do -- Jesse, I'll give you the last word. The Democrats do say that Republicans went way overboard investigating Obama, and they could point to all sorts of hearings and document requests and trying to gum up the works, and being the clown outside the airplane.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I thought those were legitimate investigations where Americans died. And Americans died in fast and furious. What's so funny, Juan?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, because --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do you think it's funny that they died in fast and furious?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'm saying --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Do you think it's funny that they've died in the end?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You've said oversight, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, you said it's totally legitimate when Republicans do it, but illegitimate when Democrats do it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's scale, Juan. If there's a dead American, I want my Congress to investigate it, Republican or Democrat. Who's dead? The only thing dead is the Democrats' electoral chances in 2020, and that's what this is all about.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Can I speak?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think that you are arguing that this president should be immune from accountability --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, I'm not.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He's been the most accountable president --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hold on. Hold on. Are you arguing --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- and more sunlight on this guy than any other president I can even remember, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: OK. So you're arguing then that if there's a conflict of interest, if he has, in fact, some kind of ties with Russia during the course --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Let Mueller decide it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Republicans --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'm willing to look at the Mueller report, Juan. You know it's not going to deliver the goods. And that's why they're doing all these other investigations.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think you're hopeful. But I'm saying Congress has legitimate responsibility. Why are you so upset when Democrats exercise that responsibility but not upset when Republicans went on for five years about --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't look upset, Juan. I'm actually happy.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Everybody is yelling and we've got to move on. All right, up next, Congressmen Ilhan Omar facing new accusation of anti-Semitism, will Democrats move to condemn her?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Welcome back. Congressman Ilhan Omar being accused of making new anti-Semitic remarks. Omar facing Republican backlash and there's some feuding with members of her own party after she said this.

utterances.speaker: REP. ILHAM OMAR, D-MINN.
utterances.utterance: Talk about the political influence in this country that says it is OK for people to push for allegiance of foreign country.

utterances.speaker: OMAR
utterances.utterance: Why is it OK for me to talk about the influence of the NRA, or fossil fuel industries, or big pharma, and not talk about a powerful lobbying group that is influencing policy?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: In response to those remarks, Democrats could vote tomorrow on a resolution to condemn anti-Semitism. The party, however, is split over whether to include Omar's name in the resolution. So, Dana, let's just go to the heart of the matter because there're people who are saying she's talking about American policy in the Middle East. Why is that anti- Semitic?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, it's because there's a code, right? So she also talks about dual loyalty. That's what she's suggesting is that people who support the State of Israel, that if they're Jewish, that you, actually -- your loyalty is not just to the United States. Your loyalty is Israel. And it's been something that has been considered anti-Semitic and goes way back. And so -- perhaps she didn't know initially that when she said that, that that was offensive. But the thing is, now she's been told so many times that you have to wonder like how do you solve -- from the musical, how do you solve a problem like Maria? I think that's what the Democrats are -- like how do you solve this problem of Congresswoman Omar because this is a story that keeps coming back over and over again. To the extent that Mark Mehlman who's a Democratic pollster, kind of guy, a consultant, they've started a group, Democrats for Israel, right? Like to explain to people why if you're Jewish and you're a Democrat, you should be supportive. And they have to do like a whole reeducation -- that's probably the wrong word. But education to people who are younger, somebody like Congresswoman Omar who is younger, but this is not -- she's not an isolated case. Like this is being taught across universities and, in particular, the BDS movement to try to divest from anything that has to do with Jewish people or Israel. That -- it's growing and so I think that there does need to be a decision by the Democrats, and I think they would be smart to go ahead and take it on now because it's clearly not going to get better.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, Jesse, in fact, a lot of people argue that this is not about Jewish people, that the biggest supporters of Israel are evangelical Christians and the Republican Party on the right that have made Israel into a sort of a litmus test for themselves. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I mean, this is universal condemnation from -- to Omar. I mean, Nancy Pelosi, the anti-defamation league, the Jewish policy center have all said that what she said is offensive and prejudice. It's not something that the evangelical right is creating here as a wedge issue. She reminds me, you know, of a freshman in college, like two weeks into the semester, first term, she's already on probation. She's already had her parents called. This is not good. I mean, she's barely a freshman and she's already getting spanked by the leadership. It's humiliating to her and it's got to be humility to the Democratic leadership right now. If you combine her with AOC's green new deal and then she stepped in with this, you know, felony campaign finance scandal, and then the other Tlaib woman with the -- impeachment rhetoric that came out of her mouth, these three radical musketeers are causing a big problem for the Democratic Party. And I guarantee you there's some picture of her with Farrakhan or someone that's about to drop. If you look -- we've talked about this the other day. She wrote that letter of support to ISIS recruits. She's traffic in anti-Semitic tropes. She's used, kind of, money language about Jewish people and their influence. And she has been educated. The Jewish community in her district in Minnesota had a big summit with her. They called it an anti-Semitic intervention and they told her this, you can't say this, this is the history of the Jewish people, and she still doesn't get it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I mean, in fact, the West Virginia GOP put up a poster, linked her to 9/11, totally illegitimate. But, again, these are attacks against her. And so, Greg, the question becomes should she be stripped of her seat on the foreign affairs committee?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't think she should have ever gotten the seat to begin with. And, you know, I have a hard time with language being over parsed because - - that's what we are doing these days on both sides. And I think the left is harder on the right in this case. I mean, they come after -- they try to believe that what you said mean something else. She can say what she wants. She just has to live with it. What bugs me about her is -- there's this other hypocrisy that she gets away with. The lesbian, gay, bisexual, LGBTQ -- am I missing one?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No, Q is the end.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Q is the end. Who are kind of -- are OK with what's not being said. So the only -- the most friendly country in the Middle East for gays is Israel, right? And that's the country she keeps harping on, and I don't think that's a coincidence because what are the other countries that -- it is definitely linked to her religious background. But that somehow skates by as everybody makes fun of Mike Pence, her religion makes Mike Pence look like Freddie Mercury. So -- I think that's something -- I think that's something that is, kind of like not discussed that probably could be raised, like, what are her thoughts? I know that she comes out in defense of the community here, but what about her affiliations to those other countries?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, Jedediah, I think the heart and soul of what she has to say is about the way Israel deals with the Palestinians. About Benjamin Netanyahu, the Israeli leader, rebuffed the U.S. on an idea of a two-state solution which had been long-term U.S. policy in the Middle East. She wants to talk about this and everybody immediately says, well, you said this and it wasn't explicitly anti-Semitic but it could be viewed that way. And she's -- she feels like she's being silenced. You can't speak out about Israel in this country.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: She's being anti-Semitic, and the problem is she has a long history of making those comments. You go back to 2012 and she was talking about, you know, Israel has hypnotized the world --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: -- she has repeatedly had to -- she's made statements that people have found deeply offensive and anti-Semitic, repeatedly had to apologize. The behavior persists. She knows that this stuff is not going to be received well. She made that comment about it's all about the Benjamins. She -- look, if she wants to make a comment about Israel, she needs to watch the way she's wording these things. She is deeply, deeply offending a vast majority of Jewish people in this country. And I think --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I don't think it's Jewish people. I think it's those Christian evangelicals --

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: No, no, please, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: She's getting condemned by the party leadership.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Yes. And she cannot say --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Not Republican Party leadership.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, because she's opening the door to these attacks.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Her name needs to be mentioned in that resolution because she is not stopping and that needs to be a deeply embarrassing moment. Democrats need to unify and say enough is enough because this doesn't -- she's doing them no favors either. Other Democrats do not want to be linked to this. Maybe AOC or other extremists can get out there in defense some of this language, but this is just not acceptable. And most Democrats know this isn't acceptable, they're not OK with it. And they're having a really hard time that someone from their party is getting away with repeatedly this type of horrific anti-Semitism.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, Joe Biden getting some bad news about 2020. Find out about that bad news next on “The Five.”

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Oh, Joe Biden is leading in 2020 polls, but he may want to think twice before jumping into the race. A focus group of Democratic voters telling the former V.P., sorry, Joe, we're just not that into you. Take a look.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: How many of you would like to see Joe Biden get in? Show of hands. What's happening?

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: His time is done.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.utterance: I'll be honest. I used to think, like, you know, because -- I was -- he was riding like the Obama wave, and I thought he was the person that would unite the party, but to be honest, you know, Senator Biden really comes from kind of the good old boy politics of the past.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Tough crowd. That same focus group also urged Hillary to stay far away from 2020, and it seems like they may get their wish, kind of.

utterances.speaker: HILLARY CLINTON, D-FORMER PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE
utterances.utterance: I'm not running, but I'm going to keep working and speaking and standing up for what I believe. I want to be sure that people understand I'm going to keep speaking out. I'm not going anywhere.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: What do you think, Juan, first about Biden, that cold reception? I seem to be hearing a lot of that that they want new blood. That they want the more progressive wing of the Democratic Party to step forward, that he's too moderate, he's too bland. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think, Jedediah, what Democrats wants is somebody who can beat Donald Trump. I think likability is number one. And so, when you start asking people about Joe Biden's politics, people will say, well, I didn't like the way he treated Anita Hill, or I don't like the way he dealt with the criminal reform bill in the '90s, or I didn't like the way that he handled some issues with President Obama, and they start bringing up all sorts of things that he said in the past. But I think when you look at the actual polls, not just the focus group of a limited number, the most recent polls had Biden with 37 percent of Democrats saying he's their number one choice, and 51 percent saying he's one of their top choices. Wow. So, I mean, right now he has the luxury of time because he's the front runner. He's got the money. He's got the staff.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: He's got the name recognition.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yes. So, I mean, Bloomberg, Mike Bloomberg the former mayor of New York, today said he's not running. Hillary Rodham Clinton says she's not running. I think a lot of them are looking to Joe Biden. There some other people on the edge, a Sherrod Brown, Terry McAuliffe who would occupy that kind of centrist lane for Democrats. And the centrist lane is very important because it has the advantage of saying I can appeal to people in such a way as to ensure we beat Trump.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Now I know you're very upset, Jesse, that Hillary is not going to be running. The only person on Earth that's more upset than you is Donald Trump. He actually tweeted about this today. You guys have that so we can read for people -- oh, there we go. Crooked Hillary Clinton confirms she will not run in 2020, rules out a third bid for the White House. Ah, shucks, does that mean I won't get to run against her again? She will be sorely missed. What do you think?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Third time is a charm, Hillary. I would say please reconsider, would love to have you back in the race.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Well, the good news is she's going to be out there stumping for people if they want her, so --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I know a lot of people don't want her. I heard a lot -- remember the last election, a lot of people didn't want her husband, Bill. They wanted to keep him at arm's length, but I bet you'd see a lot of people keeping her at arm's length, especially in some of the swing state, in the rust belt that she lost marvelously. As far as Biden goes, I agree, you know, people want the new car smell. And the zeitgeist of the Democratic Party is they want the opposite of Donald Trump. They want a young female socialist with a blank slate who can just go there and punch the president in the mouth and take him down. But everybody knows deep down, and no one knows this, deep down he knows and everybody else does, they do not have a candidate that they feel confident at this point that can beat Donald Trump and it is very hard to take out an incumbent.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Dana, what do you think Obama makes of this though. A rejection of Biden. You know people don't want Hillary Clinton around maybe potentially. I think just happens to be right on that. Is that kind of a rejection of his legacy? Does he want Biden to be the guy front and center?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think he doesn't want to have to be put in the middle and to choose and he probably understands the idea that you would want new blood and a new car smell, because he was that in 2008. And that's how he was able to beat Hillary Clinton. For Joe Biden, he has the life of a private citizen, but it comes with the scrutiny of a public official. And that's because if you look at for example the Democrats already given him a hard time, because he's out there giving $200,000 speeches or do, we have the transcripts of those speeches. Also, he's doing all these public events actively talking about whether he's going to run. He's thinking about it. They can't decide, can't decide. So, he had plenty of time to make a decision. But I think because he's put himself out there so much to keep the name recognition up that people are like, yes, we already saw that show. We don't want that show again.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: I get the desire for new blood, new ideas, freshness, I get that, but that happens to be on the Democratic side, a very extreme wing. I wonder why they're not afraid of that to put the socialist front and center, that doesn't register for them?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, the party needs new blood, but so does Joe. I can't believe we're taking this seriously. A six person focus group on CNN. I mean this was a slow news day. I give you - it was a slow news day. If we were trolling for crap off of CNN, a six person focus group. I'm sorry, it wasn't crap. It was just six people. All right. I don't trust CNN after what they did to Sanders--

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way, isn't it astounding that you and I agree.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's true. Gosh, what a night to agree. No, it's true. It's like number one, we know that C and CNN stands for Kamala. I changed the spelling. But they do take - I think they've already supported. They've already backing her. They don't want Sanders, remember how they got rid of Sanders. They don't want Joe--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Are you saying that CNN stacked the focus group.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I am saying exactly that, Jesse. I'm saying exactly - in fact, I think they all work for Kamala Harris, right. No, no, he flunks the intersectionality quiz. He's an old white male in Democratic Party terms. He's got rickets.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I don't even know what rickets are.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: But for the record, I think that focus group is dead on. I think it's representative of a lot of people.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Six person focus group.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That simple.

utterances.speaker: BILA
utterances.utterance: Company makes a surprising discovery about the gender wage gap. Details coming up next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I know. For years, the media has told us that men get paid way more than women for the same work. But when you look closely at the details, the differences tend to shrink even disappear. Take Google who has been accused of underpaying female workers. But when they investigated this charge, they found what, they indeed were underpaying men. There goes another narrative. Now this should be good news. It's progress for women, right. Instead however advocates and their supportive media simply say that equal pay must mask a more hidden discrimination. Now why would they say that? Two reasons, one for many advocates progress can be bad because an end to inequality means the advocates are out of work, so their role is less about helping people than ensuring a livelihood. Two, you lose a villain. Every day it gets harder to say men have an edge on anything. Look at education, more women graduate than men. Look at workplace death or injury, men lead that by a mile. In fact, look at all the grim stats from heart attacks to suicides to the ultimate gauge lifespan. Men are screwed from top to bottom. But in today's media landscape, gender progress is a zero-sum game meaning to elevate women, you must hammer men and if you say something like, hey, fathers' matter, that has to be an insult to women. So, even though we know both sexes complement each other, the media drives a wedge between the sexes, because it pays. When will it end? As long as their salary depends on conflict. Never had a little problem with your phone.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I apologize for that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Is that to undermine my monologue.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I didn't mean to.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You disagreed with what I was saying.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I didn't mean to. I was trying to find something that I had emailed earlier to myself about Salesforce.com. So, Salesforce.com, there is a big 60 Minutes piece on them about six months ago.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And they had done an audit and they have found that they were underpaying women.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And they were shocked by this. So, they undertook this effort to try to make sure that they brought everybody back up to parody. And one of the things that the CEO of Salesforce.com said in the interview was he encouraged every company to do an audit like this.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And they expected that the results would be that women were being underpaid everywhere. So, Google thinks we should probably do this. Now, they have fewer women working in engineering. That's a whole different problem. We can talk about that, but I am not surprised that they ended up finding this, because women have been doing a lot better and there are more women managers and there is more women on boards and so, I think that if more companies did this, they'd find that they probably have some inequality.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: So, I think that that's part of it. But to me the larger part is this, 70 percent of their workforce is male.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: And so, if you're a manager if somebody comes to you and you say, hey, there is a woman candidate, guess what, you have some discretionary money and you use the discretionary money to sweeten the pot in order to recruit the woman, so that you can say to people--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: OK.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hey, we have women who are working here and especially the case with the STEM field.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That should be the case, right, but isn't that making the opposite argument then that you used to say that people would say, well, shouldn't a manager of a company be allowed to make a decision. WATTERS: I think we need binders full of men.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: There you go.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I have a few at home.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You know Greg for me personally, I think men have really gotten a raw deal recently. The Cavanaugh situation, I think had a chilling effect.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The man bun phenomenon. But that wasn't a good look. The Gillette ad really hurt my feelings.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I mean at this point Dana I know makes more than me. There is a wage gap here at Fox.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Do you think we do the equal amount of work?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Here we go.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hold on.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's what I would say to someone else. If they were making as much as I made. But maybe all these narratives that we believe in are wrong. I mean maybe Trump is a feminist.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Maybe CNN is not fake.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He paid for his sex.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: What?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, I'm just saying that's a feminist move. He's pro sex worker.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. Kamala should support the story.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, exactly. Kamala.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
